#use wml::debian::template title="Documentation"

<p>An important part of any operating system is documentation, the technical
manuals that describe the operation and use of programs. As part of its efforts
to create a high-quality free operating system, the Debian Project is making
every effort to provide all of its users with proper documentation in an
easily accessible form.</p>

<p>If you are <em>new</em> to Debian we recommend you start first by
reading the <a href="$(HOME)/releases/stable/releasenotes">Release Notes</a>,
<a href="$(HOME)/releases/stable/installmanual.wml">Installation Guide</a>
and the <a href="manuals/debian-faq/">Debian GNU/Linux FAQ</a> before
you make your first Debian installation, it will probably answer many
questions and help you work with your new Debian system.
After the installation you might want to go through the
<a href="manuals/reference/">Debian Reference</a> and other
<a href="user-manuals">manuals</a>.
Another good source of information for newcomers is the
<a href="http://wiki.debian.org/">Debian Wiki</a>.

<p>If you want to start developing packages for Debian we recommend
you go through the <a href="manuals/maint-guide/">Debian New Maintainers' 
Guide</a> followed by the 
<a href="manuals/developers-reference">Debian Developer's Reference</a>.
Later on you can read other <a href="devel-manuals">developer manuals</a>.

<p>Most of the documentation included in Debian was written for GNU/Linux
in general. There is also some documentation written specifically for Debian.
These documents come in these basic categories:

<ul>
  <li><a href="#manuals">manuals</a>
  <li><a href="#howtos">HOWTOs</a>
  <li><a href="#faqs">FAQs</a>
  <li><a href="#other">other shorter documents</a>
</ul>


